---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Stage from "~/components/Stage.astro";
---

<Section id="pir-primer" num="02" title="PIR in one picture">
  <p>
    A PIR protocol has two guarantees worth memorizing:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Correctness.</strong> If you ask for row <code>i</code>, you
      get row <code>i</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Privacy.</strong> The server cannot learn <em>which</em> row
      you asked for — its view of the query is indistinguishable across all
      valid indices.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The mechanical implication of (2) is that the server must <em>touch every
    row identically</em>. If it could skip even one row, it would learn
    something about which row you didn't want. Every PIR backend differs in
    <em>how</em> it forces the server to touch all rows — but they all do.
  </p>

  <Stage
    caption="A query reaches the DB, every row is processed identically, a response returns. The server cannot tell which row the client wanted."
    label="PIR data-flow animation"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 260" role="img"
      aria-label="A query enters a database, sweeps over every row, and an opaque response returns."
      data-anim="primer">
      <!-- client -->
      <rect x="12" y="100" width="96" height="60" rx="8" class="svg-dim" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <text x="60" y="128" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--fg)" font-weight="600">Client</text>
      <text x="60" y="146" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">wants row i</text>

      <!-- DB rows -->
      <g transform="translate(280,40)">
        <text x="80" y="0" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">DATABASE</text>
        {Array.from({ length: 8 }).map((_, i) => (
          <g class="row" data-row={i} transform={`translate(0,${12 + i * 22})`}>
            <rect x="0" y="0" width="160" height="18" rx="4" class="svg-bg"
              stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <text x="8" y="13" font-size="10" class="svg-label">row {i}</text>
            <rect x="60" y="4" width="90" height="10" rx="2"
              fill="var(--fg-muted)" opacity="0.35"/>
          </g>
        ))}
      </g>

      <!-- server -->
      <rect x="560" y="100" width="96" height="60" rx="8" class="svg-dim" stroke-width="1.5"/>
      <text x="608" y="128" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--fg)" font-weight="600">Server</text>
      <text x="608" y="146" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">touches all</text>

      <!-- query blob -->
      <g class="blob blob-q">
        <circle r="14" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.25"/>
        <circle r="8" fill="var(--accent)"/>
      </g>
      <!-- response blob -->
      <g class="blob blob-r">
        <circle r="14" fill="var(--ok)" opacity="0.25"/>
        <circle r="8" fill="var(--ok)"/>
      </g>

      <text x="340" y="235" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">
        every row flashes identically — server learns nothing about i
      </text>
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <p>
    The animation above is a cartoon. Real PIR schemes achieve
    "touches every row identically" using clever cryptography: secret-shared
    indicator functions (DPF), homomorphic encryption (OnionPIR), or
    preprocessed hints (HarmonyPIR). The next three sections unpack each.
  </p>
</Section>

<style>
  [data-anim="primer"] .blob { opacity: 0; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .blob-q {
    opacity: 1;
    animation: qmove 1.8s var(--ease) 0.2s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .blob-r {
    opacity: 0;
    animation: rmove 1.8s var(--ease) 2.4s forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row rect:last-of-type {
    animation: flash 0.3s var(--ease) forwards;
  }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="0"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.05s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="1"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.09s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="2"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.13s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="3"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.17s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="4"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.21s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="5"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.25s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="6"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.29s; }
  [data-anim="primer"].play .row[data-row="7"] rect:last-of-type { animation-delay: 2.33s; }
  @keyframes qmove {
    0%   { transform: translate(60px, 130px); }
    60%  { transform: translate(290px, 130px); }
    100% { transform: translate(580px, 130px); opacity: 0.15; }
  }
  @keyframes rmove {
    0%   { transform: translate(580px, 130px); opacity: 1; }
    60%  { transform: translate(290px, 130px); opacity: 1; }
    100% { transform: translate(60px, 130px); opacity: 0.15; }
  }
  @keyframes flash {
    0%   { fill: var(--fg-muted); opacity: 0.35; }
    50%  { fill: var(--accent); opacity: 1; }
    100% { fill: var(--fg-muted); opacity: 0.35; }
  }
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    [data-anim="primer"] .blob { opacity: 0.25; }
    [data-anim="primer"] .blob-q { transform: translate(180px, 130px); }
    [data-anim="primer"] .blob-r { transform: translate(460px, 130px); }
  }
</style>

<script is:inline>
  document.querySelectorAll('[data-anim="primer"]').forEach((svg) => {
    const stage = svg.closest("[data-stage]");
    const run = () => {
      svg.classList.remove("play");
      void svg.getBoundingClientRect();
      svg.classList.add("play");
    };
    stage?.addEventListener("stage:visible", run);
    svg.addEventListener("click", run);
  });
</script>
